    {
      "type": "text",
      "title": "Worker Fleet & Scaling",
      "gridPos": {
        "h": 9,
        "w": 24,
        "x": 0,
        "y": 0
      },
      "id": 1,
      "options": {
        "mode": "markdown",
        "content": "\nThe worker side of **Flow 2 (Workflow Progress)** — the levers for worker tuning and the read on whether\nthe custom worker-autoscaler's scaling decisions are keeping up with load. Read it top to bottom like an incident:\n\n1. **Saturation** — is workflow/activity **schedule-to-start latency** rising? That's the canary: tasks are\n   sitting in the queue because workers can't drain fast enough (the textbook \"added pods → latency dropped\"\n   signature). Corroborate with backlog and slot utilization — backlog resets to zero on an idle queue, never\n   trust it alone.\n2. **Utilization** — *why* did latency move? Slots at zero = real capacity problem (add workers). Slots free but\n   latency high = a config/poller problem, not capacity (don't add pods). Sync match / poll success dropping =\n   pollers can't keep up with delivery.\n3. **Scaling Alignment** — did the fleet actually react? Running replica count by worker version, next to the\n   Saturation row above (same time range) — eyeball whether a scale-up event lines up with backlog/latency\n   coming back down.\n\n> **Unit trap:** these are **Core SDK (Python)** metrics. Core-based SDKs (TypeScript/Python/.NET) default to\n> **milliseconds**, Go/Java use **seconds** — but this repo's `appkit/telemetry.py` sets\n> `durations_as_seconds=True`, so every latency panel below is in **seconds** despite being a Python worker.\n> A 200ms p99 alert threshold is `0.2` here, not `200`. Don't \"fix\" the axis back to ms.\n>\n> Counters have **no `_total` suffix** in the Python SDK (e.g. `temporal_workflow_task_queue_poll_succeed`).\n>\n> **Cloud-only panels** (Sync Match Rate, Poll Success Rate by Task Type, Approximate Backlog Count) read\n> `temporal_cloud_v1_*` from the Temporal Cloud OpenMetrics scrape. They render \"No data\" on a self-hosted OSS\n> backend — that's expected, not broken. They can also show briefly blank on an idle queue since these are\n> delta metrics only emitted when there's poll/backlog activity in that scrape window.\n>\n> **Per-version backlog** (`DescribeWorkerDeploymentVersion`, what the custom worker-autoscaler acts on)\n> is now exported to Prometheus by the autoscaler itself. For the scaling decision it drives from that\n> backlog — desired vs current replicas, Cloud rate-safety, and the controller's internals — see the\n> **Platform Internals → Temporal Worker Autoscaler** dashboard. This board stays the worker-tuning /\n> fleet-reaction lens; that one is the autoscaler-decision lens.\n"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "row",
      "title": "Saturation — the Tier-1 canary + why",
      "collapsed": false,
